g.title: Folded Corner.67
g.desc: A ‘Bulky’ interface, meaning an interface with unrelated func...

g.text: A ‘Bulky’ interface, meaning an interface with unrelated functionality, can result in a module not being able to fully implement this interface. The module can resolve this by throwing a ‘not implemented’ exception. Clients whom are using this module expect the interface to be fully implemented, but an exception is thrown instead. The client is now forced to handle this. This will pollute the code with try-catch statements or checks for the concrete type. This then results in complex and less readable code.

g.title: Folded Corner.70
g.desc: This accounts for both the ‘implementing’ as ‘using’ client. ...

g.text: This accounts for both the ‘implementing’ as ‘using’ client. A module implementing a ‘bulky’, low cohesive interface is forced to implement methods it does not use. As stated in above example, this will probably result in unimplemented exceptions from certain interface methods. A ‘using’ client, iterating over an object collection of this interface, can now be forced to check for the concrete type or apply a try catch.

g.title: Folded Corner.76
g.desc: What is meant by an interface, besides the language definitio...

g.text: What is meant by an interface, besides the language definition of an interface, is everything that is publicly accessible by the ‘outside world’ (e.g. a class having public methods that can be called by other classes). An example of such a violation could be: injecting a container object inside other modules, while they do not use all the objects inside the container. Changing an object of the container would mean checking all the modules whom are injected by it. (Even when the change is unrelated for certain parts of the system).
